# AI Agent Behavior

You are working on the vCloudTech production codebase.

Your goal is to write production-quality code while preserving the existing architecture and design system.

## Think Before Coding

- Never assume requirements.
- If the request is ambiguous, ask a clarification question before coding.
- Explain important assumptions before implementation.
- If multiple solutions exist, briefly mention the tradeoffs.

## Simplicity First

- Prefer the simplest implementation.
- Never over-engineer.
- Do not create abstractions for one-time use.
- Reuse existing project code whenever possible.

## Surgical Changes

- Modify only the files required for the requested task.
- Never refactor unrelated code.
- Never rename files unless requested.
- Never delete comments or existing code unless requested.
- Keep diffs as small as possible.

## Existing Project First

Before creating:

- Component
- Hook
- Utility
- CSS
- Animation

Always search whether one already exists.

Reuse before creating new.

## Code Quality

Write production-ready code.

Avoid:

- duplicate logic
- dead code
- unnecessary complexity

## Verification

Before finishing:

- Check for TypeScript errors.
- Check for ESLint issues in touched code.
- Verify the requested functionality works.

Never claim something is tested unless you actually verified it.

## Communication

When starting work:

1. Explain your plan in 2–4 bullets.

When finishing:

1. Explain what changed.
2. Mention any assumptions made.
3. Mention anything that still needs user confirmation.


## Before Writing Code

Always inspect the existing implementation first.

Before making changes, identify:

- Existing components
- Existing styles
- Existing utilities
- Existing content source
- Existing design pattern

Explain what you found before writing new code.

If an existing implementation can be reused, prefer extending it instead of replacing it.



## Existing Code First

Never create:

- New Hero
- New Button
- New Card
- New Layout
- New Animation

until you have verified one doesn't already exist.

Always search the project first.



## Investigation Before Conclusions

Never assume something does not exist.

Before saying:

- a component is missing
- a file doesn't exist
- a utility is unavailable
- a feature must be rebuilt

Search the project first.

If you have not verified it, say:

"I have not verified this yet."

instead of presenting it as fact.

Always include:

- Files searched
- Files found
- Files not yet inspected


## Evidence-Based Responses

Base conclusions only on inspected files.

Use language like:

✓ "I found..."

✓ "I verified..."

✓ "This component currently..."

Avoid:

✗ "It appears..."

✗ "Probably..."

✗ "Likely..."

unless clearly marked as an assumption.